VERDICT: not-confirmed
REASON: The underlying code observation is factually accurate: ffi/src/lib.rs:5414 hardcodes MEM_DOMAIN_MAX_PARTITIONS=16 while zephyr/gale_mem_domain.c sizes its stack arrays at CONFIG_MAX_DOMAIN_PARTITIONS. However, both concrete failure modes require a SoC that overrides the Kconfig default of 16 — only fvp_aemv8r (AArch64=8, AArch32=24) and nsim arc_classic/hs (32) do so. Neither is in gale's declared target list (README/renode-multi-arch-ci.md: Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4F STM32F4, Cortex-M33 STM32L552, Cortex-R5 ZynqMP). SWREQ-MD-MD04 (requirements.yaml:4001-4005) explicitly fixes the design bound at "CONFIG_MAX_DOMAIN_PARTITIONS = 16", which matches the Rust const. On every target gale builds for, CONFIG evaluates to 16 and no OOB or MD1-skip occurs. Per validate.md step 4, "the scenario requires a hardware configuration outside gale's declared target list" → not interesting. Hardening (passing num_partitions_cfg + startup assert) is still a good defensive change, but does not constitute a confirmed bug under gale's supported configurations, and the existing C-side __ASSERT(max_partitions <= CONFIG_MAX_DOMAIN_PARTITIONS) at gale_mem_domain.c:413 already gates the only other loose coupling.
